== IoT
#title-slide("Internet of Things", "Connecting the Physical World")

#topic[What is IoT?]

Network of physical devices — sensors, actuators, microcontrollers — that collect data and/or act on the physical world, connected to each other and/or the internet.

#note[#text(weight: "bold", fill: teal-color)[Core idea:] embed connectivity and processing into everyday objects, enabling remote monitoring, control, and automated decision-making.]
#example[smart thermostats, industrial sensors, wearables, connected cameras.]

---

#align(center)[#image("../../../assets/iot.png", width: 80%)]
#footer("Visual generated by AI")
---

#topic[IoT Architecture]

+ *Perception layer*: sensors, actuators, microcontrollers _(e.g. ESP32)_ — gathers raw data from the physical environment.
+ *Network layer*: transports data between devices, gateways, and the cloud _(WiFi, BLE, LoRa, cellular)_.
+ *Application layer*: processes, stores, and presents data — dashboards, alerts, automated actions.

---

#topic[IoT Communication Protocols]

- *HTTP/REST*: simple request/response, good for infrequent commands.
- *WebSocket*: persistent, full-duplex — used where low-latency bidirectional updates are needed _(e.g. live sensor dashboards)_.
- *MQTT*: lightweight publish/subscribe over TCP, designed for constrained devices and unreliable networks — the de-facto standard for IoT telemetry.
- *CoAP*: UDP-based, REST-like, built for very constrained devices.

---

#topic[Edge Computing in IoT]

- Processing data *on or near the device*, rather than sending everything to the cloud.
- #text(weight: "bold", fill: eg-green)[#checkmark Benefits:] lower latency, reduced bandwidth use, works with intermittent connectivity, improved privacy.
- Edge AI: running trained ML models directly on microcontrollers _(e.g. TinyML on ESP32)_ for local inference, no round trip to a server.

---

#topic[A Typical IoT Stack]

- *Device*: ESP32 _(or similar)_ reads sensors, runs local logic, optionally an on-device ML model.
- *Broker*: MQTT broker _(e.g. Mosquitto on a Raspberry Pi or cloud VM)_, routes messages between devices and applications.

#example[dashboard or service subscribing to topics, visualizing data, triggering alerts or actions.]

