#title-slide[LoRa & LoRaWAN][Long-Range, Low-Power Wireless for IoT]

#titlebar[What is LoRa?]

- *LoRa* (Long Range) — a proprietary spread-spectrum radio modulation, Chirp Spread Spectrum (CSS), developed by Semtech.
- Runs in unlicensed sub-GHz ISM bands: *868 MHz* (Europe, Africa, Middle East — ITU Region 1), *915 MHz* (US/Canada), 433/470 MHz regionally.
- Trades throughput for range and power: kilometers of reach at a few hundred bps to ~50 kbps.
- LoRa is the *physical layer only* — modulation and radio, nothing else.

#important[
  LoRa ≠ LoRaWAN. LoRa is the radio modulation (PHY). *LoRaWAN* is the open MAC/network protocol built on top of it, standardized by the LoRa Alliance. You can use raw LoRa point-to-point without ever touching LoRaWAN — that's exactly what the demo later in this section does.
]

#slide[
  #titlebar[Where It Fits]
  #align(center)[
    #table(
      columns: (auto, auto, auto, auto, auto),
      stroke: 0.5pt + gray,
      inset: 6pt,
      text(weight: "bold")[Technology],
      text(weight: "bold")[Range],
      text(weight: "bold")[Power],
      text(weight: "bold")[Data Rate],
      text(weight: "bold")[Topology],

      [Wi-Fi], [~50 m], [High], [High (Mbps)], [Star (AP)],
      [BLE], [~10-30 m], [Low], [Medium], [P2P / mesh],
      [LoRa / LoRaWAN], [2-15+ km], [Very low], [Very low (bps-kbps)], [Star-of-stars],
      [NB-IoT / LTE-M], [Cellular coverage], [Low-medium], [Low-medium], [Cellular],
      [Zigbee], [~10-100 m], [Low], [Medium], [Mesh],
    )
  ]
  #note[
    LoRa doesn't replace MQTT or WebSocket from earlier in this section — it replaces Wi-Fi/Ethernet as *how a device reaches the network in the first place*. MQTT still runs on top, just past the gateway.
  ]
]

#align(center)[#image("../../../assets/bandwidth-power-range.webp", width: 70%)]
#footer[Source: #link("mokolora.com/lora-and-wireless-technologies/")]

#slide[
  #titlebar[Why It Fits IoT]
  - *Long range* — several km in urban areas, 15+ km rural / line-of-sight.
  - *Low power* — years of battery life on a coin cell; suits battery- or energy-harvested sensors.
  - *Penetration* — sub-GHz propagates through walls and foliage better than 2.4 GHz Wi-Fi/BLE.
  - *Low data rate by design* — built for a sensor reading every few minutes, not a video stream. Trade-off, not a flaw.
  - *Star-of-stars topology* — many end devices → a handful of gateways → one network server (unlike Wi-Fi's single-hop AP model).

  #note[
    Same spirit as MQTT: devices don't need to know who's listening. Here the *gateway* does the decoupling, over the air, instead of a broker doing it over TCP.
  ]
]

